The '''casual''' [[subculture]] is a subsection of [[association football culture|football culture]] that is typified by [[football hooliganism|hooliganism]] and the wearing of expensive [[designer clothing]]<ref>{{cite news | title=Casuals: The Lost Tribe of Britain: They dressed, andf still dress, cool and fought | work=[[The Sunday Herald]] | date=8 May 2005 | author=Barry Didcock | url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12493851.CASUALS___THE_LOST_TRIBE_OF_BRITAIN_They_dressed_cool_and_fought_dirty__but_their_impact_on_fashion_has_been_largely_ignored__Now_they_are_making_a_comeback_______in_bookshops/ |accessdate=11 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | title=Hit and Tell: a Review Essay on the Soccer Hooligan Memoir | author=Steve Redhead | journal=[[Soccer and Society]] | volume=5 |issue=3 | date=Autumn 2004 | pages=392–403 | doi=10.1080/1466097042000279625 | url=http://www.pierretristam.com/pdfs/wc1.pdf }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | title=Components of dress: design, manufacturing, and image-making in the fashion industry | author=Juliet Ash, Lee Wright (chapter author: Deborah Lloyd) | edition=illustrated | editor=[[Routledge]] | year=1988 | isbn=0-415-00647-3 | pages=100–106 | chapter= Assemblage and subculture: the Casuals and their clothing |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=03w9AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA100&lpg=PA100&dq=casuals+subculture }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Pundit says: 'learn to love the casuals' | work=[[The Sunday Herald]] 2005-05-08 | author=James Hamilton | url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4156/is_20050508/ai_n14619610 | date=8 May 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | ref = ken_gelder | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=USl1G-903EwC&pg=PA91&vq=casuals+subculture+skinheads+mods+hippies | page=91 | title = The Subcultures Reader | author = Ken Gelder (chapter author: Phil Cohen) | editor = [[Routledge]] | year = 2005 | accessdate = 2008-08-15 | chapter=Subcultural conflict | isbn = 978-0-415-34416-6}}</ref> (known as "clobber"). The subculture originated in the United Kingdom in the early 1980s when many hooligans started wearing designer clothing labels and expensive sportswear such as [[Stone Island]], [[CP Company]], [[L'alpina]], [[Lacoste]], [[Sergio Tacchini]], [[Fila (company)|Fila]] and [[Ellesse]] in order to avoid the attention of police and to intimidate rivals.{{cn|date=July 2018}} They did not wear club colours, so it was allegedly easier to infiltrate rival groups and to enter [[pub]]s. Some casuals have worn clothing items similar to those worn by [[Mod (subculture)|mods]].{{cn|date=July 2018}} Casuals have been portrayed in films and television programmes such as ''[[I.D. (1995 film)|ID]]'', ''[[The Firm (1989 film)|The Firm]]'' and ''[[The Football Factory (film)|The Football Factory]]''.{{cn|date=July 2018}}

==History==
The designer clothing and fashion aspect of the casual subculture began in the mid-to-late 1970s.  One well documented precursor was the trend of Liverpool youths starting to dress differently from  other football fans — in [[Peter Storm (clothing)|Peter Storm]] jackets, straight-leg jeans and [[Adidas]] [[Athletic shoe|trainers]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Allt|first1=Nicholas|title=The Boys From The Mersey|date=2004|publisher=MILO|isbn=1 903854 39 3|pages=39–54|edition=first}}</ref> [[Liverpool F.C.]] fans were the first British football fans to wear continental European fashions, which they picked up while following their teams at matches in Europe.<ref name="bbc website">{{cite news|title=bbc-british style genius|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/britishstylegenius/content/22265.shtml|accessdate=2013-08-19|date=2013-08-19}}</ref>

The other documented precursor, according to Colin Blaney, was a subculture known as ''Perry Boys'', which originated in the mid-1970s as a precursor to the casuals. The Perry Boys subculture consisted of Manchester football hooligans styling their hair into a flick and wearing sportswear, [[Fred Perry#Clothing label|Fred Perry]] shirts and Dunlop Green Flash trainers.<ref>{{cite book |first=Colin |last=Blaney |title=Undesirables |year=2014 |publisher=John Blake |isbn=978-1782198970 |pages=7}}</ref>

