The '''''Classic of Arts''''' (Chinese: [[wikt:艺|艺]][[wikt:经|经]], pinyin: Yi Jing) was a 3rd-century Chinese book written by Handan Chun on the various cultivated arts of ancient China.<ref>{{cite book|title=Chinese aesthetics: the ordering of literature, the arts, and the universe in the Six Dynasties|author=Cai, Zongqi|publisher=[[University of Hawaii Press]]|year=2004|isbn=0-8248-2791-0|page=350}}</ref><ref name=game>{{cite book|title=Asian games: the art of contest|authors=MacKenzie, Collin and Irving L. Finkel, Asia Society. Museum, Arthur M. Sackler Gallery (Smithsonian Institution)|publisher=Asia Society, original from [[University of Michigan]]|year=2004|isbn=0-87848-099-4|page=188}}</ref> The book also briefly discussed some basics of the [[Go (board game)|game of go]], and it was the first to state the [[9 Pin Zhi]], a system for [[Go ranks and ratings]].  Although the earliest surviving complete manual on the game is the 6th century ''[[Dunhuang Go Manual]]''.

