'''Gammuladani''',<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dassanayaka|first1=Channa|title=Introduction from Sri Lankan Flavours|url=https://www.cooked.com/uk/Channa-Dassanayaka/Hardie-Grant-Books/Sri-Lankan-Flavours/Introduction|website=Cooked.}}</ref> '''Gammuladeni''',<ref name=matara /><ref name="HasbullahMorrison2004">{{cite book|author1=S. H. Hasbullah|author2=Barrie M. Morrison|title=Sri Lankan Society in an Era of Globalization: Struggling To Create A New Social Order|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TJCHAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA177|date=10 August 2004|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=978-81-321-0320-2|page=177}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Past Times: "When Life was Simple"|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/000102/sup5.html|work=The Sunday Times (Sri Lanka)|date=2 January 2000}}</ref> or '''Grammuladani'''<ref name=matara>[http://www.matara.ds.gov.lk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4&Itemid=43&lang=en "Overview"], Matara Divisional Secretariat</ref> is a former [[Sinhala language|Sinhala]] term for a [[village headman]] in [[Sri Lanka]]. Other terms were ''[[arachchi]]'', ''gamika'',<ref name="Silva1981">{{cite book|author=K. M. De Silva|title=A History of Sri Lanka|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dByI_qil26YC&pg=PA322|date=January 1981|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-04320-6|page=23}}</ref> ''gammudaliya'',<ref name="Clough1982">{{cite book|author=B. Clough|title=Sinhalese English Dictionary|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CmrJwQoPcsgC&pg=RA2-PA592|year=1982|publisher=Asian Educational Services|isbn=978-81-206-0105-5|page=155}}</ref> ''gammudalia'',<ref>{{cite book|title=The Journal of the Ceylon Branch of the Royal Asiatic Society of Great Britain & Ireland|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1hkYAAAAYAAJ|year=1894|publisher=The Branch|page=238}}</ref> or ''vidane''. 

During the [[British Ceylon|colonial period]] the village headman had wide-ranging powers: his tasks included investigating crimes, coordinating agricultural activities, collecting taxes, and issuing permits for access to land.<ref name="Wenzlhuemer2008">{{cite book|author=Roland Wenzlhuemer|title=From Coffee to Tea Cultivation in Ceylon, 1880-1900: An Economic and Social History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nTewCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA197|year=2008|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-474-3217-3|page=197}}</ref> The post was replaced in the 1960s by the government-appointed [[Grama Niladhari]] (previously ''Grama Sevaka'').<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fernando|first1=Austin|title=SLAS – 50 Not Out!|url=https://www.colombotelegraph.com/index.php/slas-50-not-out/|work=Colombo Telegraph|date=17 February 2014}}</ref><ref name="GunatilakaWilliams1999">{{cite book|author1=Ramani Gunatilaka|author2=Tushara Williams|author3=World Bank|author4=United Nations Development Programme|title=The integrated rural development programme in Sri Lanka: lessons of experience for poverty reduction|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-OXZAAAAMAAJ|year=1999|publisher=Institute of Policy Studies (Colombo, Sri Lanka)|page=37}}</ref><ref name="Peebles2015">{{cite book|author=Patrick Peebles|title=Historical Dictionary of Sri Lanka|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=50igCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA159|date=22 October 2015|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|isbn=978-1-4422-5585-2|page=159}}</ref>

